d Areas in Mexico -- tPART IV. The Economics of Community Forestry -- tChapter 11: Vertical Integration in the Community Forestry Enterprises of Oaxaca -- tChapter 12: The Managerial Economics of Sustainable Community Forestry in Mexico: A Case Study of El Balcón, Técpan, Guerrero -- tPART V. Global Comparisons and Conclusions -- tChapter 13: The Global Significance of Mexican Community Forestry -- tChapter 14: Community Forestry in Mexico: Twenty Lessons Learned and Four Future Pathways -- tAppendix: Acronyms Used -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMexico leads the world in community management of forests for the commercial production of timber. Yet this success story is not widely known, even in Mexico, despite the fact that communities around the globe are increasingly involved in managing their own forest resources. To assess the achievements and shortcomings of Mexico's community forest management programs and to offer approaches that can be applied in other parts of the world, this book collects fourteen articles that explore community forest management from historical, policy, economic, ecological, sociological, and political perspectives. The contributors to this book are established researchers in the field, as well as many of the important actors in Mexico's nongovernmental organization sector. Some articles are case studies of community forest management programs in the states of Michoacán, Oaxaca, Durango, Quintana Roo, and Guerrero. Others provide broader historical and contemporary overviews of various aspects of community forest management. As a whole, this volume clearly establishes that the community forest sector in Mexico is large, diverse, and has achieved unusual maturity in doing what communities in the rest of the world are only beginning to explore: how to balance community income with forest conservation. In this process, Mexican communities are also managing for sustainable landscapes and livelihoods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCommunity forestszMexico. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh1 aAlatorre-Guzmán, Enrique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmbinakudige, Shrinidhi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntinori, Camille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarry, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarry, Deborah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoyer, Christopher R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBray, David Barton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBray, David Barton, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChapela, Francisco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurán, Elvira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerez-Fernández, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuevara-Sanginés, Alejandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlooster, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez-Arzola, Rodolfo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMas, Jean-François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerino-Pérez, Leticia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerino-Pérez, Leticia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNavarro-Martínez, María Angélica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSegura-Warnholtz, Gerardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary